\begin_layout Chapter
Determinism Tests and Bohmian Mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rationale
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As was pointed out in the previous chapter, it is known that BM doesn't
 assign a unique value to spin of a particle.
 For BM, spin is only a property of the wavefunction.
 Recall that the GHZ test was formulated for spins.
 Consequently, the conclusion that spins can't have pre-defined values (determin
istic) does not contradict BM outright.
 Precisely how the GHZ test is compatible with BM, is worth exploring.
 It will edify our understanding of how to analyse a physical situation
 using BM and the relation between determinism & non-locality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the point of view of QM however, the treatment of spins is not fundamentall
y different from that of phase-space variables (position 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

).
 It is not surprising therefore, that the GHZ test can be generalized to
 phase space and at least one such extension is known 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GHZcontinuous"

\end_inset

.
 The conclusion one draws from the phase space GHZ test, would then be that
 
\begin_inset Formula $q,\,p$
\end_inset

 can't have pre-defined values.
 This then, is in direct contradiction with BM, which claims that 
\begin_inset Formula $q,\,p$
\end_inset

 are precisely defined and their evolution completely determined (given
 the initial position, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

, and the wavefunction).
 Since it is believed that BM is completely consistent with QM, it is of
 considerable interest to explore how BM can resolve the apparent paradox.
 If it fails, then we would have identified a way to falsify BM.
\end_layout

