\begin_layout Subsection
Compatibility with BM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To analyse any situation using BM, one is required to know the experimental
 arrangement.
 In this case, we assume that spins are measured using the Stern-Gerlach
 (SG) apparatus.
 Without loss of generality, let us assume that the initial state of the
 particle is given by, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\left|\Psi(\vec{r}_{1},\vec{r}_{2},\vec{r}_{3},t=0)\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{+++}(\vec{r}_{1},\vec{r}_{2},\vec{r}_{3},t=0)\right\rangle \otimes\left|000\right\rangle -\left|\psi_{---}(\vec{r}_{1},\vec{r}_{2},\vec{r}_{3},t=0)\right\rangle \otimes\left|111\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents the position vector in the frame of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 observer.
 Note that the explicit tensor product is used to separate the spin and
 position parts the three particles.
 If the wavefunction for each particle is assumed to be Gaussian initially,
 propogating along their respective axes of the SG apparatus, then one can
 further simplify the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{\pm\pm\pm}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 It has been shown 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BohmGHZetc"

\end_inset

 that the time evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{\pm\pm\pm}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 can be written as products of 3 single particle solutions of the SG setup,
 which was analyzed by Bohm himself.
 Once 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi(\vec{r}_{i},t)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is known, one can evaluate the equation of motion for the three particles,
 using BM.
 If the SG apparatus are setup to measure say XYY, then from both numerical
 simulations & analysis of the trajectory equations, the following is observed
 in the direction relevant to measurement.
 Four attractor basins are formed: 
\begin_inset Formula $(+++)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(+--)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(-+-)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(--+)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 represent the physical location in the SG, corresponding to a spin `up'
 (`down') measurement.
 The product is always 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

, consistent with predictions of QM.
 However, when the SG apparatus are setup to measure XXX, the trajectories
 are found to obey equations which possess four attractive basins: 
\begin_inset Formula $(---)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(-++)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(+-+)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(++-)$
\end_inset

.
 Again, the product is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, in agreement with QM.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a remark, it maybe stated, that the details of evaluating the trajectory,
 become complicated rather quickly and that it is not trivial to obtain
 analytic solutions for the phase-space scenario.
 Consequently, numerical simulations are a necessity beyond this stage.
 (See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BohmGHZetc"

\end_inset

 for a flavour of the complexity)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, one finds that non-locality enters the description from the
 fact that the attractor basins which form, depend on the settings of 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 SG apparatus.
 Thus, we learn that while all the results are deterministic, they depend
 on the precise experimental setup, and not merely operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Phase Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To extend the GHZ test to phase space, note first that we need only the
 following situation.
 Consider instead of observables (which are Hermitian), unitary operators,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 with the following redefinitions: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\equiv\hat{X}^{\dagger}\otimes\hat{Y}\otimes\hat{Y}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}\equiv\hat{Y}^{\dagger}\otimes\hat{X}^{\dagger}\otimes\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}\equiv\hat{Y}\otimes\hat{Y}^{\dagger}\otimes\hat{X}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}=\hat{X}\otimes\hat{X}\otimes\hat{X}$
\end_inset

.
 If these unitary operators also satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{X},\hat{Y}\}=0=\{\hat{X},\hat{Y}^{\dagger}\}$
\end_inset

, then it follows that (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}$
\end_inset

 all commute and (b) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\hat{B}\hat{C}\hat{D}=-\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

.
 Now any simultaneous eigenket of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A},\,\hat{B},\,\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}$
\end_inset

 will yield a GHZ situation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see why that will work, replace the unitary operators with complex numbers
 and note that the unitary property translates to each of these numbers
 being uni-modular.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $ABC=X^{*}\otimes X^{*}\otimes X^{*}$
\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{*}Y=1$
\end_inset

 for each particle.
 This would entail that 
\begin_inset Formula $ABC=D^{*}$
\end_inset

, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $ABCD=1$
\end_inset

.
 However we also know that 
\begin_inset Formula $ABCD=-1$
\end_inset

, which yields the contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another patent issue with this scheme, is the use of unitary operators,
 as opposed to observables.
 This issue is resolved by explicit construction, however the idea can be
 motivated in general.
 If an arbitrary unitary operator, is a function of some fixed observable,
 and that alone, then one can measure the said observable.
 From this, the value of the unitary operator can be evaluated, thereby
 dissolving the objection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Known Extension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possible construction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GHZcontinuous"

\end_inset

, involves the use appropriate displacement operators.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}\equiv e^{i\sqrt{\pi}\hat{q}/L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}\equiv e^{i\sqrt{\pi}\hat{p}L}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is some length scale and units are s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=1$
\end_inset

 (for this section).
 These satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\hat{X},\hat{Y}\}=0$
\end_inset

, which follows trivially by recalling that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{p}u}e^{i\hat{q}v}=e^{i\cancelto{1}{\hbar}uv}e^{i\hat{q}v}e^{i\hat{p}u}$
\end_inset

.
 To construct a simultaneous eigenstate, observe that for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sqrt{2}\left|\uparrow\right\rangle _{q_{0},p_{0}} & \equiv & \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}e^{i\sqrt{\pi}2kp_{0}L}\left|q=\sqrt{\pi}L\left(q_{0}+2k\right)\right\rangle \\
 &  & +i\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}e^{i\sqrt{\pi}(2k+1)p_{0}L}\left|q=\sqrt{\pi}L\left(q_{0}+2k+1\right)\right\rangle ,\\
\sqrt{2}\left|\downarrow\right\rangle _{q_{0},p_{0}} & \equiv & \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}e^{i\sqrt{\pi}2kp_{0}L}\left|q=\sqrt{\pi}L\left(q_{0}+2k\right)\right\rangle \\
 &  & -i\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}e^{i\sqrt{\pi}(2k+1)p_{0}L}\left|q=\sqrt{\pi}L\left(q_{0}+2k+1\right)\right\rangle ,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}L/\sqrt{\pi}$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\pi}Lq_{0}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\in[0,1)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}\left|\uparrow\right\rangle =\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}\left|\uparrow\right\rangle =i\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}\left|\downarrow\right\rangle =\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}\left|\downarrow\right\rangle =-i\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (we have dropped 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 for simplicity).
 This also holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}^{\dagger}\left|q\right\rangle =\left|q+\sqrt{\pi}L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}\left|x\right\rangle =e^{i\sqrt{\pi}q/L}\left|q\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 If one defines 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}=i\hat{Y}\hat{X}$
\end_inset

, from the aforesaid, it follows 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}\left|\uparrow\right\rangle =\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}\left|\downarrow\right\rangle =-\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The problem has been made sufficiently analogous to the original GHZ test.
 It is now immediate that the required simultaneous entangled eigenket must
 be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\psi\right\rangle =\frac{\left|\uparrow\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle -\left|\downarrow\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

It is obvious that for obtaining the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

, one need only measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}$
\end_inset

 and their conjugates.
 We have therefore an extension of the GHZ test to continuous variables.
 To understand how BM explains this however, one must be able to simulate
 this.
 The test in the given form, is not simple to simulate, since the states
 involved have infinite spread in position space (infact one can show that
 even in momentum space the spread is infinite).
 Further, the wavefunction in position space, is a countable union of disjoint
 delta functions.
 Neither of these are desired from the numerical point of view.
 The latter can be handled by integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle _{q_{0},p_{0}}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 with an appropriate weight.
 However, no simple way could be conceived of to suppress the infinite spread.
\end_layout

