\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Z}\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle =-\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 In addition to this, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}=e^{-i\hat{p}L/\hbar}$
\end_inset

 (note that this is not Hermitian).
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{\pm}\right\rangle \equiv\frac{\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle +\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 is not an eigenstate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

, although it comes close.
 We optimize the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}'\equiv\hat{X}\hat{T}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}\equiv e^{i\hat{p}NLa(\hat{q})/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(q)=\begin{cases}
1 & 2L<q<4L\\
0 & \text{else}
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

The idea is that you shift certain peaks to the right place, before applying
 the displacement operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

.
 To illustrate this, consider explicitly 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle =\left(\left|\varphi_{-4}\right\rangle +\left|\varphi_{-2}\right\rangle +\left|\varphi_{-1}\right\rangle +\left|\varphi_{-3}\right\rangle \right)/\sqrt{4}$
\end_inset

.
 The operation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}\left|\varphi_{4}\right\rangle =\left|\varphi_{-5}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}\left|\varphi_{3}\right\rangle =\left|\varphi_{-6}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}\left|\varphi_{n}\right\rangle =\left|\varphi_{n}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\{-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2\}.$
\end_inset

 It is now evident that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}'=\hat{X}\hat{T}\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}'^{\dagger}\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}'\left|\psi_{1}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}'^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 does the same.
 So finally, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle \equiv\left(\left|\psi_{0}\psi_{0}\psi_{0}\right\rangle -\left|\psi_{1}\psi_{1}\psi_{1}\right\rangle \right)/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\equiv\hat{X}'\otimes\hat{Y}'\otimes\hat{Y}'^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Y}'\equiv i\hat{Z}\hat{X}'$
\end_inset

, calculations yield 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}\equiv\hat{Y}'^{\dagger}\otimes\hat{X}'\otimes\hat{Y}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}\equiv\hat{Y}'\otimes\hat{Y}'^{\dagger}\otimes\hat{X}'$
\end_inset

 also, by symmetry we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}\equiv\hat{A}\hat{B}\hat{C}=\hat{X}'\otimes\hat{Y}'\hat{X}\hat{Y}'^{\dagger}\otimes\hat{X}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}\equiv\hat{X}'\otimes\hat{X}'\otimes\hat{X}'$
\end_inset

 yield the paradox.
 If values were predefined, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}$
\end_inset

 would return the same answer.
 However, a simple calculation yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{E}\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle =\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (this can be seen directly by applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A},\,\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 sequentially on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

), while 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{D}\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle =-\left|\psi_{G}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
