\end_inset

 parametrizes the sequence and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, the time step.
 To get reasonably accurate results, one needs to keep 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 small.
 This is known as the Euler method and it has errors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\Delta t^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 However, there's another known method, popularly referred to as ``RK4'',
 short for Runge Kutta 4, which has errors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\Delta t^{5})$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming again that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}=f(q)$
\end_inset

, the method claims that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n+1}=q_{n}+\frac{h}{6}(k_{1}+2k_{2}+2k_{3}+k_{4})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n+1}=t_{n}+h$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
k_{1} & = & f(q_{n}),\\
k_{2} & = & f(q_{n}+hk_{1}/2),\\
k_{3} & = & f(q_{n}+hk_{2}/2),\\
k_{4} & = & f(q_{n}+hk_{3}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $h=\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 The derivation is tangential to our interest and will have to be skipped.
 The advantage is that this method can produce accurate results for relatively
 larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 also.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our purpose is to solve the Schr
