\end_layout

\end_inset

dinger Equation, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\psi/\partial t=-(\hbar^{2}/2m)(\partial^{2}\psi/\partial q^{2})+V(q)\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly this is more complicated than the case discussed before, for now
 we have to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a function of both 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 We begin with uniformly discritizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 in the position space, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is known only at finite points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 to start with (and has spacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q$
\end_inset

), while time is discritized as usual, with step 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 Imagine that we are at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{th}$
\end_inset

 step, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 are known, and so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

 (where the notation means that at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{th}$
\end_inset

 step, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 is known at all the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\{q_{i}\}$
\end_inset

).
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

, one can evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial^{2}\psi/\partial q^{2}=\psi''$
\end_inset

 using the definition of the derivitive, without imposing the 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to0$
\end_inset

 limit (in the usual notation) and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi''(q_{i})=\left[\psi(q_{i+1})-2\psi(q_{i})+\psi(q_{i-1})\right]/(\Delta q)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The objective is to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n+1}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

, which according to the Euler method can be evaluated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n+1}(q_{i})=\left[-\psi''(q_{i})+V(q_{i})\psi\right]\Delta t$
\end_inset

, where for illustration, we have set 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar^{2}/2m=1$
\end_inset

.
 Practically this doesn't suffice and we are forced to use RK4 (or any better
 alternative).
 To use RK4, one must be careful and remember that we are evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 for a given value 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore in the evaluations of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 must be kept fixed, for here 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is the variable, playing the role of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 Ofcourse, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a complex variable Accordingly, we must have, suppressing 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 to avoid confusion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n+1}=\psi_{n}+\frac{h}{6}(k_{1}+k_{2}+k_{3}+k_{4})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
k_{1} & = & -\psi_{n}''+V\psi_{n},\\
k_{2} & = & -(\psi_{n}+hk_{1}/2)''+V(\psi_{n}+hk_{1}/2),\\
k_{3} & = & -(\psi_{n}+hk_{2}/2)''+V(\psi_{n}+hk_{2}/2),\\
k_{4} & = & -(\psi_{n}+hk_{3})''+V(\psi_{n}+hk_{3}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $h=\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 Let us take a moment to understand how one must go about evaluating this
 numerically.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}''(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 are known, one can evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 trivially.
 To evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 however, we would require 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

 to be known (or at least 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}(q_{i-1})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}(q_{i+1})$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, we first evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\,q_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the grid.
 Then to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{n}+hk_{1}/2)''$
\end_inset

, evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the finite difference method requires it's argument to be known at
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i+1}$
\end_inset

, we see that knowing 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

 is sufficient to evaluate this step.
 One similarly evaluates 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

 to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{3}(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{4}(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

.
