\begin_layout Subsubsection
Simulation of trajectories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to Bohmian Mechanics, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}=p/m=\nabla S/m=\hbar\text{Im}(\nabla\psi/\psi)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=Re^{iS/\hbar}$
\end_inset

.
 From the previous section, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

, discretized 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 at each time step.
 We conclude therefore, that the simplest way to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla S$
\end_inset

 at an arbitrary position, is to interpolate 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and subsequently evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla S$
\end_inset

.
 Spline interpolation is quite standard and fairly simple to extend to complex
 variables.
 The details will not be discussed here, but the code written [see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:BM-Simulation-Results"

\end_inset

] can be referred to.
 It maybe mentioned that given 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\{q_{i}\})$
\end_inset

, one can evaluate spline co-efficients, using which, one can easily (in
 a computationally cheap way) evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(q)$
\end_inset

 for practically any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 To evolve 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, viz.
 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}$
\end_inset

, again RK4 was used where this time, there are no complications.
 To be able to better appreciate the results, one needs to plot multiple
 trajectories simultaneously.
 The mildly non-trivial aspect of this part, is that one needs to start
 with particles distributed according to 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Attempts were made to find a library that can do this, but with no luck.
 A method to convert a uniform random distribution to an arbitrary distribution
 was independently arrived at, for a course on Numerical Methods.
 The idea was to use a uniform random generator, with range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, which for the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 particle, yields 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{(j)}$
\end_inset

, say.
 The method is that, from the cumulative 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(q)=\int_{-\infty}^{q}\left|\psi(q')\right|^{2}dq'$
\end_inset

 , one finds 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{(j)}$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(q^{(j)})=c^{(j)}$
\end_inset

, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{(j)}=\phi^{-1}(c)$
\end_inset

.
 The inverse is guaranteed to be single valued, because the cumulative is
 monotonically increasing.
 While a formal proof can be presented, we will satisfy ourselves with noting
 the following.
 Intuitively, a range of positions with high probability, will cause a larger
 range of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 values to yield those positions, making them more likely to appear; since
 all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are equally likely.
 With all these ingredients combined, Bohmian trajectories were successfully
 simulated.
\end_layout

