\begin_layout Standard
Measurement of spins in BM was discussed in the previous chapter.
 Our interest in this chapter, is in measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and functions there of.
 We will learn that one can infact construct a universal method that facilitates
 the measurement of any arbitrary observable.
 The analysis will clarify two notions which are at high risk of being misconstr
ued.
 First, that the position of the particle, when measured, will infact yield
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 However, a measurement of momentum of a particle, as we will see, does
 not always yield 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (the value it had prior to measurement).
 Infact, it would be inconsistent with QM if it did; for instance, consider
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(q)=\left(1/\sqrt{\pi}\right)e^{-q^{2}}$
\end_inset

, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

 and therefore so is 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\nabla S=0$
\end_inset

.
 However it is known that upon measurement of momentum, one obtains a distributi
on given by the fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Although this is centred around the origin, it is not a delta function
 (has non-zero spread).
 The second notion which is clarified, is that to find the value obtained
 upon measurement of certain observables, knowledge about the precise position
 of the measuring particle (the particle used to make the measurement) can
 play a deciding role.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Observable with discrete spectrum | Hamiltonian Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bohm has discussed in his second paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bohm2"

\end_inset

, how any arbitrary observable maybe measured, in BM.
 To describe a measurement, we use a measuring particle (mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{L}$
\end_inset

, say), by getting it to interact with the system for a short duration appropria
tely.
 Subsequently, we measure the final position of the particle, to learn about
 the value of the observable of interest.
 Say for instance, we wish to measure the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

, then the required interaction Hamiltonian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{\text{int}}=a\hat{L}\otimes\hat{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Here the first operator acts on the system and second (after the tensor
 product symbol) acts on the measuring particle.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 quantifies the interaction strength.
 It has dimensions of frequency, if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 has dimensions of length.
 Let us assume that the system in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Then it is known that one can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\sum_{l}\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|l\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are the eigenstates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 (we have assumed non-degenercy for simplicity, but its removal doesn't
 cause any significant difficulty).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{S}(t)\right\rangle =\hat{U}(t)\left|\psi\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{U}(t)=e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[-\hbar^{2}\frac{\nabla_{1}^{2}}{2m}-\hbar^{2}\frac{\nabla_{2}^{2}}{2m_{L}}+\hat{H}_{\text{int}}\right]t}
\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the state of the measuring particle, given by a Guassian centred at
 the origin, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(q)=(1/\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma)e^{-q^{2}/2\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is very small, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 very large, s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $at=\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a finite number, then one can neglect the free evolution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}t$
\end_inset

 terms compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{\text{int}}t$
\end_inset

.
 We then have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\Psi_{S}(t)\right\rangle  & = & e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}a\hat{L}\otimes\hat{p}t}\left|\Psi_{S}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \sum_{l}\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle \otimes e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\lambda l\,\hat{p}}\left|\varphi\right\rangle \\
 & = & \sum_{l}\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi_{\lambda l}\right\rangle ,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi_{q_{0}}\right\rangle =\int dq\varphi(q-q_{0})\left|q\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 This interaction, effectively entangles the measuring particle, with the
 possible `outcomes', eigenstates of the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 of interest.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\ll\lambda l$
\end_inset

, then according to QM itself, a position measurement of the measuring particle,
 would correspond, in a one-to-one way, to the eigenstate/eigenvalue of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

, to which the system will collapse.
 In the context of BM, after the interaction, the measuring particle would
 be guided into one of these eigenstates, and a position measurement would
 yield the same.
 We glossed over various details in making the last statement, which will
 be delineated shortly, through some illustrations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Generalization to observables with continuum spectrum 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:BM-measurement-to-continuous"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are interested in observing phase space variables, the aforesaid
 must be generalized to the continuous spectrum regime.
 We proceed with the aforesaid notation, and promote the discrete operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 to have a continuous spectrum.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\int dl\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, and recall 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi\right\rangle =\int dq\varphi(q)\left|q\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(q)$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 quantifying the deviation from the origin.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{S}(t)\right\rangle =\hat{U}(t)\left|\psi\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi\right\rangle =\int\int dldq\varphi(q)\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle \otimes\left|q+l\lambda\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=at$
\end_inset

 as before.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is measured at this stage and 
\begin_inset Formula $q'$
\end_inset

 is the value obtained.
 The resultant state would then be 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|q'\right\rangle \left\langle q'\right|\left|\Psi_{S}\right\rangle =\int\int dldq\varphi(q-l\lambda)\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle \delta(q-q')=\int dl\varphi(q'-l\lambda)\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(q)\approx0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $q\notin(-\delta q,\delta q)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q=\mathcal{O}(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 can be chosen, depending on the accuracy desired.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $-\delta q<q'-l\lambda<\delta q$
\end_inset

, which entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $l=\frac{q'}{\lambda}\pm\frac{\delta q}{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 We thus have a relation between the observed position, 
\begin_inset Formula $q'$
\end_inset

, of the measuring particle, and the value of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The error is controlled by the sharpness of the initial state of the measuring
 particle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Consistency check; measurement of position 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:BM-Consistency-check-measurement"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The position of a particle, as is claimed by BM, remains the same upon observing.
 Let us verify this statement, by applying the aforesaid formalism.
 For simplicity, let us assume that the state of the system is given as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\left|\psi\right\rangle =\int dq\left[\delta(q-q_{0})+\delta(q+q_{0})\right]\left|q\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, which is to say, the system is in a superposition of being at 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us assume that the particle is initially given to be in 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Now our measurement formalism must be consistent with this, viz.
 the answer must not depend on the initial position of the measuring particle.
 Initially then, the state is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{S}\right\rangle =\left|\psi\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, while after interaction, the state becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\left|\Psi_{S}(t)\right\rangle =\left|q_{0}\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi_{\lambda q_{0}}\right\rangle +\left|-q_{0}\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi_{-\lambda q_{0}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 To understand this clearly, one must plot 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{S}(q_{1},q_{2})\right|^{2}=\left|\left\langle q_{1},q_{2}|\Psi_{S}\right\rangle \right|^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|q_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is (the position eigenket) for the system and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|q_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for the measuring particle.
 
